Categorical Cross entropy (CCE) is a loss function commonly used in multi-class classification problems. It measures the difference 
between two probability distributions, typically the true labels and the predicted probabilities.

here we have multiple classes and the model outputs a probability distribution over those classes.

These are for classificaition

CCE = -(1/n)  (sigma i=1 to n)  (yi * log(y^i))


yi = actual class label ie if it belongs to class then 1 else 0


data points         class X   class Y    class Z        actual class
point 1             0.7       0.2        0.1             class X
point 2             0.1       0.8        0.1             class Y
point 3             0.2       0.3        0.9             class Z


so the CCE = loge(0.7) + loge(0.8) + loge(0.9) = -0.35667 - 0.22314 - 0.10536 = (-0.68517)*(-1/3)= 0.22839



here the activation function used is softmax as we are dealing with multi class classification
 and it converts the output of the model into a probability distribution over the classes. 
 The softmax function takes a vector of real numbers as input and normalizes it into a probability 
 distribution, where each value is between 0 and 1, and the sum of all values is equal to 1. This
  allows us to interpret the output of the model as probabilities for each class, which is essential
   for calculating the categorical cross-entropy loss.